[normal]&#xa0;[bold]DCLG Select Committee inquiry into Local Government Procurement[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Written e[bold]vidence s[bold]ubmitted by the[bold] West London Alliance[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Background[bold] to the West London Alliance[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The WLA is a partnership of six
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]West London councils - Barnet, Brent, Ealing, Harrow, 
[normal]Hillingdon and Hounslow.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]These councils serve a population of 1.8 million people and have a joint annual expenditure of £3.8bn a year. There are over 77,000 VAT registered business and nearly 700,000 employees active in this West London area.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The WLA a
[normal]ims to: promote the interests of West London residents and businesses; improve and develop public services; and to reduce their costs through collaboration.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In addition to
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]representing the interests of West London in terms of economic development, transpor
[normal]t and spatial planning policy, the WLA
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]facilitates a number of major improvement and efficiency programmes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The WLA is also a founder member of the West London Partnership (WLP) which brings together the public, private and voluntary sectors in West Lond
[normal]on to promote the economic, social and environmental interests of West London businesses and residents.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Executive Summary[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The [bold]West London Alliance[bold] coordinates collaborative procurement activity with and on behalf of member boroughs[bold]&#xa0;[bold]There are currently 
[normal]seven major
[normal] 
[normal]improvement and efficiency programmes in which WLA members collaborate when programmes align with their council’s objectives and plans.  Some programmes also involve working with other councils in London, particularly the Tri-Boroughs (Hammersm
[normal]ith &amp; Fulham, Westminster and the Royal Borough of Kensington &amp; Chelsea).  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The seven programmes are;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Further programmes are in development
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As well as improving services, the aim is to achieve savings
[normal] and/
[normal]or avoi
[normal]d costs. The area target for this is at least £57m in the period up to 2016/17.  Programme delivery has been supported by grant aid from a number of sources, particularly Capital Ambition.  DCLG grant was awarded to LBH&amp;F on behalf of the WL Housing Partne
[normal]rship, while the WestTrans Partnership secured grant from the TfL Sub Regional Fund.
